{"timestamp": "2025-11-29 17:23:31.643438", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — SDN spine–leaf lab\nDate: (current state snapshot)\n\n1) Executive summary\n- Symptom: Hosts in 10.0.0.0/24 are isolated from each other — all host-to-host pings fail (100% loss) and ARP resolution fails.\n- Control/management plane: Switches and hosts’ management interfaces (20.0.0.0/24) are up and can reach the SDN controller (20.0.0.100). The Open vSwitch (OVS) bridges are configured to use the controller and are in fail_mode \"secure\".\n- Likely root cause (high probability): Data-plane forwarding rules are not present/active on the OVS switches (leaf switches are not forwarding host L2 traffic). This appears to be an SDN control->data-plane provisioning issue (either the controller hasn’t installed flows, or the OpenFlow session / flow programming for host forwarding is not established), resulting in complete L2/L3 isolation for hosts on 10.0.0.0/24.\n\n2) Key abnormal behaviors detected\n- All inter-host pings (any host -> any other host in 10.0.0.0/24) returned \"Destination Host Unreachable\" from the source — 100% packet loss for ICMP across the host subnet.\n- Host ARP/neighbor entries show other hosts as FAILED (no ARP responses).\n- Host interfaces are UP and have correct IP addresses; hosts are transmitting frames (TX counts > 0) but receive nothing from peers (RX counts = 0).\n- Leaf/spine OVS bridges are configured with a controller (tcp:20.0.0.100:6633) and fail_mode is secure (explicitly configured to rely on controller-installed flows).\n- Management-plane connectivity (20.0.0.0/24) from switches to controller is healthy — switches can ping controller successfully.\n\n3) Evidence and relevant command outputs (high-level)\n- Ping matrix: all host -> host attempts returned Destination Host Unreachable and 100% packet loss.\n- Host network config (examples):\n  - host_1_1: eth0 inet 10.0.0.1/24; TX packets non-zero, RX 0.\n  - host_1_2: eth0 inet 10.0.0.2/24; TX non-zero, RX 0.\n  - host_2_1: eth0 inet 10.0.0.3/24; TX non-zero, RX 0.\n  - host_2_2: eth0 inet 10.0.0.4/24; TX non-zero, RX 0.\n- ip neigh on hosts: entries for other hosts marked \"FAILED\".\n- OVS on switches (example leaf_1):\n  - Bridge leaf_1\n    - Controller \"tcp:20.0.0.100:6633\"\n    - fail_mode: secure\n    - Ports: eth0, eth1, eth2, internal\n- Switch IPs (management):\n  - leaf_1 eth3 20.0.0.2/24\n  - leaf_2 eth3 20.0.0.3/24\n  - spine_1 eth2 20.0.0.1/24\n- Ping to controller:\n  - leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1 -> 20.0.0.100 succeeded (0% loss, low RTT)\n\n4) Localization — where the fault lies\n- Problem localized to the OVS data plane (leaf switches) responsible for forwarding host traffic on the 10.0.0.0/24 subnet.\n  Evidence:\n  - Host frames reach the leaf switch NICs (host TX seen on leaf eth0/eth1 RX counters), but the leaf does not forward these frames to other host-facing ports nor to spine interfaces (no corresponding TX or spine-facing RX on the leaf).\n  - ip neigh FAILED on hosts indicates ARP requests are not being answered — implies ARP not being forwarded/handled by switches.\n  - OVS bridges are in secure fail_mode: without controller-installed flows, Linux/OVS will not perform normal fallback learning/forwarding — consistent with observed complete isolation.\n\n5) Probable root cause(s) and rationale\n- Primary probable root cause: Missing or inactive data-plane forwarding flows on the OVS switches (controller has not installed forwarding rules for the host-subnet).\n  - Rationale:\n    - OVS is configured to use an external controller and is in fail_mode secure (so data-plane forwarding depends on the controller).\n    - Management-plane connectivity to the controller is OK, but hosts remain isolated, which is consistent with either:\n      - the controller application is not programming host forwarding rules (controller app absent/misconfigured), or\n      - the switches have an OpenFlow session problem (controller reachable by IP but OpenFlow handshake/session or role negotiation not established), or\n      - flows were flushed/never installed for the 10.0.0.0/24 tenant network.\n- Alternative/less likely causes (not ruled out yet):\n  - Physical/cable mis-wiring at the datapath (less likely because leaf port RX counters show host traffic arriving, but no forwarding occurs).\n  - Bridge or datapath misconfiguration on OVS (for example ports not attached to the bridge datapath or ports administratively down). However port states show UP/LOWER_UP and RX counts on host-facing ports indicate links are up.\n\n6) Additional observations that support the diagnosis\n- OVS bridge fail_mode = secure: In this mode, OVS will drop packets not matched by flow entries. If the controller does not insert flows, switching will not happen and ARP will fail.\n- The management network (20.0.0.0/24) is healthy and controller is reachable from switches; the control-plane connectivity alone does not guarantee correct flow programming by the controller.\n\n7) Suggested next diagnostic checks (to confirm root cause — no remediation recommended here)\n(These are suggested validation steps to confirm the diagnosis; I did not perform them yet)\n- On each OVS switch:\n  - Check OpenFlow connection state: ovs-vsctl show / ovs-appctl or ovs-ofctl show <bridge-name> to see controller connection state and OpenFlow channel status.\n  - Dump switch flow tables: ovs-ofctl dump-flows <bridge-name> — confirm whether there are flows for host MACs / IPs / ARP handling.\n  - Check ovs logs and controller logs for FLOW_MOD errors or authentication/role negotiation failures.\n- On the controller:\n  - Confirm the controller application (the forwarding app) is running and has learned host attachments.\n  - Inspect controller logs for errors pushing flows to switches or OpenFlow handshake issues.\n- Optionally: capture packet traces on leaf host-facing interfaces (tcpdump) to observe ARP requests and whether any ARP replies or forwarded frames are ever emitted by the switch.\n\n8) Confidence level\n- High confidence that hosts are isolated due to lack of data-plane forwarding rules on OVS (controller flow programming / OpenFlow session issue). Evidence: hosts can reach mgmt/controller IPs, leaf ports receive host frames but do not forward them, OVS in secure fail_mode.\n\n9) Final remark\n- The current failure is a data-plane forwarding failure (L2/L3 forwarding absent) resulting in complete host isolation on the 10.0.0.0/24 tenant network. Management-plane (controller reachability) is intact, which narrows the issue to controller application behavior or the OpenFlow control-plane/session to the OVS datapath rather than basic IP connectivity.\n\nIf you want, I can run the next validation commands (ovs-ofctl dump-flows, ovs-ofctl show <bridge>, controller log checks, or packet captures) to further confirm which of the two likely root causes (controller not programming flows vs. OpenFlow session failure) is the actual cause.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 12950, "output_tokens": 3454, "total_tokens": 16404, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 12160}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1792}}}
